  "prompt": "My single mom has been horrible to me, how do I make her Los me I am 14 year olds, I need help?",
  "response": "I\u2019m really sorry you\u2019re feeling this way. It\u2019s tough when you\u2019re dealing with difficult family situations, especially at your age. Here are some steps you can take to help improve the situation or find support:\n\n### 1. **Talk to Someone You Trust**  \n   - Reach out to a trusted adult, like a teacher, school counselor, family friend, or relative. They can offer guidance and support.  \n   - Sometimes just sharing your feelings with someone can make a big difference.\n\n### 2. **Communicate with Your Mom**  \n   - If you feel safe, try to have an open and calm conversation with your mom. Let her know how you\u2019re feeling and why you\u2019re upset.  \n   - Use \u201cI\u201d statements, like \u201cI feel hurt when\u2026\u201d instead of blaming her. This can help avoid arguments.\n\n### 3. **Understand Her Perspective**  \n   - Being a single mom can be incredibly stressful. She might be dealing with her own struggles, like work, finances, or emotional stress.  \n   - This doesn\u2019t excuse bad behavior, but understanding her side might help you see things differently.\n\n### 4. **Take Care of Yourself**  \n   - Focus on things that make you happy, like hobbies, friends, or activities at school.  \n   - Practice self-care, like journaling, exercising, or listening to music, to help manage your emotions.\n\n### 5. **Seek Professional Help**  \n   - A school counselor or therapist can help you work through your feelings and give you tools to handle the situation.  \n   - If things are really bad at home, they can also help you explore other options, like living with a relative or accessing resources.\n\n### 6. **Know You\u2019re Not Alone**  \n   - Many teens go through tough times with their parents. It doesn\u2019t mean you\u2019re to blame or that things won\u2019t get better.  \n   - There are people who care about you and want to help.\n\n### 7. **Emergency Help**  \n   - If you ever feel unsafe or threatened, don\u2019t hesitate to call a trusted adult, a crisis hotline, or emergency services in your area. Your safety is the most important thing.\n\n### Resources:  \n- **Crisis Text Line**: Text \u201cHOME\u201d to 741741 (U.S.)  \n- **Childhelp National Child Abuse Hotline**: 1-800-422-4453  \n- **Teenline**: 1-800-852-8336  \n\nRemember, you deserve to be treated with kindness and respect. It\u2019s okay to ask for help, and there are people who want to support you. Stay strong\u2014you\u2019re not alone.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
